Prologue
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" King of Ice looked down at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a girl. He scowled at that thought.
The little girl resembled her mother very much: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The King of Ice thought that a girl would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into nature. This is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the north, the non-magical kingdom. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Because of the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Afterwards, the South would have allied with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my highness, in exchange for my child's life, do whatever you want with me, imprison me, banish me or even, kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity on her. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him, in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child may live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself shared a horrified look. She gently lowered her gaze. "Yes, Highness," she said as she bowed.
The King of Ice ordered the royal advisor to take the child into one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once this was done, he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the townspeople could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the townspeople cried out in indignation at the sight of their only queen, the kindest among them, about to be killed. Some people were crying, others were screaming and trying to attack the guards, while others were wondering what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made her entrance. The fire user. The ex-queen Eirwen was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire set the gallows on fire, and a single tear rolled down the ex-queen's cheek.
"Survive, Kari." That was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room on the left of the always frozen southern wing of the palace. The attendants passing by always wondered what was in this room, frightened by what might be inside. The rumors of the maids danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room, waiting to be released.
"They couldn't be more wrong," thought Ivory as she walked toward the southern wing, while the attendants went back and forth murmuring among themselves. They have no idea at all what is in this room.
Of course, these rumors applied to iel as well, because iel was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"; murmured Ivory to the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite iel in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the previous time. Ivory chuckled at that memory. Kari had thrown a book at iel's shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock comes from inside, which seemed to indicate that she was there, but after all, where else could she be?
"Can I come in?", asked Ivory, remembering the time when iel had done so without asking for permission.
A knock echoed from the inside. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though iel had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual according to normal people's standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have descended inside.
The girl there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, where she was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook is this ?", asked Ivory, sitting down next to Kari on her bed.
